 The tendency is to want to finish the race as soon as possible and get a head start on recovering from it.
 But the mist burned off and the last eight miles -- the toughest portion of the marathon -- became even tougher.
 The refrain from the runners was, "It's not the heat, it's the humidity." The men's race was led at various times by a pack of about six runners.
 Viktor Gural of the Soviet Union, who had been among the leaders for most of the race, said he had trouble with everything.
 Guadalupe Roman of Mexico led through much of the race but lost ground steadily in the last five miles and finished sixth.
